Notebook[{
Cell["Problem Set 15 \[LongDash] Also Goes with Chapter 11", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.980612196187374*^9, 3.980612211422606*^9}, {
  3.983968223819804*^9, 3.9839682248940153`*^9}, {3.9839695309872723`*^9, 
  3.983969535158185*^9}, {3.983980615438734*^9, 
  3.983980622471321*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"821ff873-b417-423b-a8a4-\
5a0d4019d7d8"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["For Quantum Mechanics, Monday, Apr. 6, 2026", "Subtitle",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.980620822912372*^9, 3.980620841363928*^9}, {
  3.9839682338068867`*^9, 3.9839682414390907`*^9}, {3.983980527357904*^9, 
  3.983980530247429*^9}, {3.9839806287273607`*^9, 
  3.98398062886162*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"cfc20ab9-f802-4f42-a532-\
dae68ab4fb47"],

Cell["\<\
The reading that goes with this problem set is III-11-6. Also look ahead and \
read III-16-1, which is your first reading on the Schrodinger Equation which \
applies to probability amplitudes that depend on position.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.983968514603891*^9, 3.983968519566084*^9}, {
  3.983969208149592*^9, 3.983969221078026*^9}, {3.983980541318819*^9, 
  3.983980543838336*^9}, {3.983981165199122*^9, 3.983981168151512*^9}, {
  3.983981221209655*^9, 
  3.983981259548587*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"78dd3dcc-f0bf-4b02-97f8-\
7d7ae53d90e0"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["  1. Exponential and Trig Functions of Pauli Matrices", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9806122473340683`*^9, 3.980612272489726*^9}, {
   3.980621891551169*^9, 3.980621896529681*^9}, {3.9839682628456497`*^9, 
   3.9839682667006483`*^9}, {3.9839683063812027`*^9, 3.983968307248416*^9}, {
   3.983968355074514*^9, 3.983968406625751*^9}, {3.983977711544046*^9, 
   3.983977712396945*^9}, 3.98397808148806*^9, {3.983978543592001*^9, 
   3.983978544567422*^9}, {3.983980609303006*^9, 
   3.983980609780491*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"bd7f4c6f-2807-4ccb-9228-\
6374abf56214"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "This is just a bit more mechanical practice, but quite suggestive practice, \
that helps you start seeing the convenience of working with Pauli matrices.\n\
\n(a) Derive/check the identities in Table 11-2 using Table 11-1.\n(b) What \
is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"cos", " ", 
    SubscriptBox["\[Alpha]\[Sigma]", "x"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "1799b62d-3472-4fde-871e-10930dc1bea2"],
 "? Use the Taylor series for cosine to define the cosine of a matrix.\n(c) \
What is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"sin", " ", 
    SubscriptBox["\[Alpha]\[Sigma]", "x"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "bf4ba7a4-2fb5-42ca-9b78-59d8569ef6d0"],
 "? Use the Taylor series for sine.\n(d) What is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["e", 
    RowBox[{"i", "\[VeryThinSpace]", "\[Alpha]", "\[VeryThinSpace]", 
     SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "x"]}]], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "f7df0109-a8bf-45cd-afac-a0a110802e97"],
 "? Use the Taylor series for the exponential.\n(e) What is the relation \
between the quantities in (b), (c), and (d)?\n(f) With no significant \
additional work what is the relationship between ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["e", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"-", "i"}], "\[VeryThinSpace]\[VeryThinSpace]", "\[Mu]", "\[VeryThinSpace]", 
     SubscriptBox["B", "x"], 
     SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "x"], 
     RowBox[{"t", "/", "\[HBar]"}]}]], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a64e9e6e-da24-451d-98bc-2b0340aaafb3"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"cos", " ", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"-", "i"}], "\[VeryThinSpace]\[VeryThinSpace]", "\[Mu]", "\[VeryThinSpace]", 
      SubscriptBox["B", "x"], 
      SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "x"], 
      RowBox[{"t", "/", "\[HBar]"}]}], ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"fa000920-3e92-4851-8867-3f866c1aa366"],
 ", and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"sin", " ", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"-", "i"}], "\[VeryThinSpace]\[VeryThinSpace]", "\[Mu]", "\[VeryThinSpace]", 
      SubscriptBox["B", "x"], 
      SubscriptBox["\[Sigma]", "x"], 
      RowBox[{"t", "/", "\[HBar]"}]}], ")"}]}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"f4b663e1-5546-403f-8a93-4c80cc9738dd"],
 "?\n(g) As a rhetorical question, can you see that the result you got in (f) \
might be extremely useful?"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.983969364740806*^9, 3.983969465751883*^9}, {
  3.983980658010148*^9, 3.983980680493806*^9}, {3.983981266975162*^9, 
  3.983981727384842*^9}, {3.983981944013588*^9, 
  3.983982132488153*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"abef8f8c-45e2-4e75-9cb6-\
33160743448f"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["2. Feynman Problem for 78.4 for Chapter 11", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9806122473340683`*^9, 3.980612272489726*^9}, {
  3.980621891551169*^9, 3.980621896529681*^9}, {3.983968256411457*^9, 
  3.983968270948419*^9}, {3.983968311269022*^9, 3.98396831338275*^9}, {
  3.983968373071863*^9, 3.983968373146867*^9}, {3.983968413422265*^9, 
  3.983968427328349*^9}, {3.9839806118529987`*^9, 
  3.983980612015799*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"413cda28-8731-45f7-8881-\
d270e9897077"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "You will need Section III-11-6 for this problem. Feynman has a sneaky way \
of attacking the problem that does not require the determinant of a 6x6 \
matrix. Read what he suggests as an approach for finding ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["E", "I"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "ca66f23c-1c91-42a1-a02b-c548cd95108d"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["E", 
    RowBox[{"I", "\[VeryThinSpace]", "I"}]], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "14541036-cda1-424c-b4cc-b3df7a5b5c79"],
 ", etc., and the associated ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["C", 
    RowBox[{"I", ",", "\[VeryThinSpace]", "i"}]], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "f68b6487-8040-4fe7-a9c5-8a045388af86"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["C", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"I", "\[VeryThinSpace]", "I"}], ",", "\[VeryThinSpace]", "i"}]], 
   TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "36550799-7495-4443-8e9a-843acd99f750"],
 ", etc.\n\nIt might be helpful to do the same problem but with only 3 atoms \
in the ring first. There will be less algebra to balloon the problem up with. \
However, once you have done it for 3 and 6 atoms, probably you can write your \
answer in a nice way that does it once and for all for a ring of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["N", TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "61c2a718-7352-43ae-8fa0-7ecc388a1c34"],
 " atoms."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.983968489643042*^9, 3.9839684980536623`*^9}, {
  3.983969472770564*^9, 3.983969493936009*^9}, {3.9839805670783978`*^9, 
  3.983980604907061*^9}, {3.983980699606298*^9, 3.98398075611285*^9}, {
  3.983981747536149*^9, 3.9839818545939627`*^9}, {3.983982141402486*^9, 
  3.983982141940474*^9}, {3.983982172378468*^9, 
  3.983982184480595*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"5f6555fc-195c-41aa-a879-\
31dd949e3d68"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]]
},
